PCA by cov and corr with standardized

Because of the variance of marathon is so large, so we standardized all data first, then do the PCA.

#############pca by cov and corr with standardized
male.z=scale(male[,1:8])
female.z=scale(female[,1:7])

#male
male_pca_by_cov <- princomp(male.z, cor = F)
summary(male_pca_by_cov, loadings = T)

The Kolmogorov-Smirnov test is defined by:

H0: The data follow a specified distribution | 
H1: The data do not follow the specified distribution

(In here, the specified distribution is the Normal distribution - "pnorm" )

By the result, whatever we choose Alpha = 0.05 or 0.005, we can see that all data are not close to Normal. So we apply the Power Transformation.

Power Transformation

#male
male_after = male[,1:8]
for (i in 1:8){
  male_after[,i] <- predict(boxcox(male[,i]))}
#female
female_after = female[,1:8]
for (i in 1:7){
  female_after[,i] <- predict(boxcox(female[,i]))}

By the result, after Power Transformation, we let Alpha = 0.05 :

  • for male

not reject H0 {100m , 200m , 400m , 800m , 1500m , 10000m} > follow Normal

reject H0 {5000m , marathon } > not follow Normal

  • for female

not reject H0 {100m , 200m , 400m , 800m , 1500m , 3000m ,marathon } > follow Normal
